HEADWORD: Lorn
<hw>Lorn</hw> <pr>(l⟦ocir⟧rn)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Strong p. p. of
<er>Lose</er>. See <er>Lose</er>, <er>Forlorn</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Lost; undone; ruined.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If thou readest, thou art <qex>lorn</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Forsaken; abandoned; solitary; bereft; <as>as, a
lone, <ex>lorn</ex> woman</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>


